      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im trying to make hollandaise for brunch and it just totally broke... it looks all oily and separated now. why does that happen??",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the classic \"separated hollandaise\" disaster! It's a tragedy of culinary physics, much like when a goblin tries to sneak into a castle without a key and gets stuck in the lock. The secret ingredient, egg yolks, are essentially tiny, fragile goblins that love to be whipped into a creamy, smooth paste. If you overheat them or let them sit too long, they lose their magic and turn into greasy, oily blobs that refuse to blend.\n\nIt's like trying to make a smoothie with a blender that's been left on for too long; the ingredients have lost their cohesion. To fix it, you need to whisk the yolks vigorously with a little bit of hot milk or cream while you're making the sauce, keeping the heat low and the whisk moving fast. If you see those oily spots forming, it's because the goblins have been exposed to too much heat or time, so you'll need to whisk them again until they regain their creamy, smooth texture.\n\nDon't worry, it's not your fault! Just remember that goblins need to be kept warm and fed properly to stay happy and creamy. Now, let's get that sauce back together!",
